'''''Han Solo and the Lost Legacy''''' is a [[Star Wars Legends|''Star Wars'' Legends]] novel written by [[Brian Daley]]. It is the third and final volume of the ''[[Star Wars: The Han Solo Adventures]]'' series, and it was first published by [[Del Rey]] in [[August]] [[1980]]. The complete trilogy was reprinted in [[The Han Solo Adventures (omnibus)|''The Han Solo Adventures'']] ([[1992]]).

==Publisher's summary==
''The fabled hoard of the mad tyrant Xim was beyond measure&mdash;it was also, as far as Han Solo and his Wookiee partner Chewbacca were concerned, strictly legendary. But the pleadings of an old spacebum who had once saved his life&mdash;plus the fact that a trifling misunderstanding had set the deadliest gunman in the galaxy on his trail, making a secret expedition to almost any place seem highly desirable&mdash;were enough to grab Han Solo's interest.''

''But within hours of landing on the planet rumored to hold the treasure, Han's beloved spacecraft ''Millennium Falcon'' was hijacked, and his party had to content with assassins and an army of killer robots.''

''This was no way, Han Solo felt, for a pair of honest smugglers to make a living&hellip;''

==Plot summary==
Han Solo and Chewbacca are back on hard times, having squandered their "reward" for breaking up the [[Slavery/Legends|slavery]] ring within the [[Corporate Sector Authority/Legends|Corporate Sector Authority]]. Once again, the smuggler duo is teamed with the elderly [[Labor droid/Legends|labor droid]], [[BLX-5]], and the [[Computer probe/Legends|computer probe]], [[Blue Max]].

A quick job nets the smugglers 1,500 [[Galactic Credit Standard/Legends|credits]] and lands them on the [[University of Rudrig/Legends|University]] world of [[Rudrig/Legends|Rudrig]] in the [[Tion Hegemony/Legends|Tion Hegemony]]. Here, Han and Chewie encounter [[Alexsandr Badure]], an old smuggler who had once saved their lives. Badure has fallen on hard times himself and has been working contract labor at a quasi-legal [[Mining/Legends|mining]] camp on the planet [[Dellalt/Legends|Dellalt]], where he has befriended two sisters, [[Hasti Troujow|Hasti]] and [[Lanni Troujow]]. Lanni, a [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]], has discovered what they believed to be the [[log-recorder]] disk from the long-lost [[Queen of Ranroon/Legends|''Queen of Ranroon'']], the fabled treasure ship of the [[Warlord/Legends|warlord]] Xim the Despot. [[Millennium/Legends|Millennia]] earlier, the ''Queen'' and her cargo of treasure, and a legion of Xim's [[war-robot]]s, were lost en route to Xim's sprawling treasure vaults on Dellalt.

Badure needs Han and Chewbacca for a [[Mission to Dellalt|mission]], taking himself and Hasti back to Dellalt, along with the [[Ruurian/Legends|Ruurian]] professor [[S. V. Skynx/Legends|Skynx]], whose job was to translate the disk and lead them all to the treasure. Lanni stashes the disk in a lockbox at the vaults, before being murdered by the mine operators, who pursue Badure and Hasti to claim the disk and treasure for themselves.

Han is being pursued by [[Gallandro/Legends|Gallandro]], the deadliest gunman in the [[Galaxy/Legends|galaxy]], who was bent on avenging a point of honor with Han over their dealings in the [[Corporate Sector/Legends|Corporate Sector]]. Shortly after arriving on Dellalt, the mine operators manage to steal the ''Millennium Falcon'' and take it back to the mine to search for the disk. Han's party decides to hike across several hundred [[Kilometer/Legends|kilometers]] of Dellatian open country to reclaim her. Along the way, they met up with the [[Survivors (Dellalt)|Survivors]], a clan of inbred [[Human/Legends|Humans]] who have evidently lived in the mountains for generations and kept their existence secret.

==Continuity==
The [[2018]] film ''[[Solo: A Star Wars Story]]'' references ''Han Solo and the Lost Legacy''; in the film, the [[mytag crystal]] [[masthead of Xim the Despot]] is one of the artifacts aboard the ''[[First Light]]''.<ref name="SW">{{SW|url=news/4-amazing-easter-eggs-from-dryden-vos-study|text=4 Amazing Easter Eggs from Dryden Vos' Study}}</ref>

